{"type":"message","id":"ccf140a7","parentId":"2e0380b3","timestamp":"2026-03-16T00:00:37.385Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_145cca1b00ad4d97882313eb","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\"type\":\"session\",\"version\":3,\"id\":\"bb63b19c-96a3-492d-9563-7e6363a69526\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:00.084Z\",\"cwd\":\"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace\"}\n{\"type\":\"model_change\",\"id\":\"f922f7a4\",\"parentId\":null,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:00.085Z\",\"provider\":\"qianfan\",\"modelId\":\"glm-5\"}\n{\"type\":\"thinking_level_change\",\"id\":\"f6365c15\",\"parentId\":\"f922f7a4\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:00.085Z\",\"thinkingLevel\":\"off\"}\n{\"type\":\"custom\",\"customType\":\"model-snapshot\",\"data\":{\"timestamp\":1773532800094,\"provider\":\"qianfan\",\"modelApi\":\"openai-completions\",\"modelId\":\"glm-5\"},\"id\":\"4227066d\",\"parentId\":\"f6365c15\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:00.094Z\"}\n{\"type\":\"message\",\"id\":\"a6c1b380\",\"parentId\":\"4227066d\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:00.113Z\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"[cron:c0707b44-d291-4e3b-8399-91bbb500d041 Daily 8AM Report] Generate and send a comprehensive daily report for yesterday. Read memory/daily/YYYY-MM-DD.md, diary/YYYY-MM-DD.md, and morning chat logs from yesterday. Include: 1) Key activities and work completed, 2) Important learnings and insights, 3) Progress on projects, 4) Notable conversations or decisions, 5) Plans or next steps mentioned. ALSO: Check OpenClaw PR #24218 status using 'gh pr view 24218 --repo openclaw/openclaw' and include any updates in the report. Send the complete report to Feishu.\\nCurrent time: Sunday, March 15th, 2026 — 8:00 AM (Asia/Shanghai) / 2026-03-15 00:00 UTC\\n\\nReturn your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically. If the task explicitly calls for messaging a specific external recipient, note who/where it should go instead of sending it yourself.\"}],\"timestamp\":1773532800107}}\n{\"type\":\"message\",\"id\":\"4cc1af1b\",\"parentId\":\"a6c1b380\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:07.658Z\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"I need to generate a daily report for yesterday (March 14th, 2026). Let me:\\n1. Read the daily memory file for yesterday\\n2. Read the diary file for yesterday\\n3. Read morning chat logs from yesterday\\n4. Check the OpenClaw PR #24218 status\\n5. Compile everything into a comprehensive report\\n\\nLet me start by reading the relevant files and checking the PR status.\",\"thinkingSignature\":\"reasoning_content\"},{\"type\":\"toolCall\",\"id\":\"call_33989cb3e3934d289d7780f6\",\"name\":\"read\",\"arguments\":{\"file_path\":\"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-14.md\"}},{\"type\":\"toolCall\",\"id\":\"call_6fced52d9a2b483ab49860ae\",\"name\":\"read\",\"arguments\":{\"file_path\":\"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/diary/2026-03-14.md\"}},{\"type\":\"toolCall\",\"id\":\"call_bcae073eeec44e0e85b6f5a1\",\"name\":\"exec\",\"arguments\":{\"command\":\"gh pr view 24218 --repo openclaw/openclaw\"}},{\"type\":\"toolCall\",\"id\":\"call_0df7784371db441b80d8da6c\",\"name\":\"exec\",\"arguments\":{\"command\":\"ls -la /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/chat/ | grep -E \\\"2026-03-14|20260314\\\"\"}}],\"api\":\"openai-completions\",\"provider\":\"qianfan\",\"model\":\"glm-5\",\"usage\":{\"input\":20845,\"output\":240,\"cacheRead\":0,\"cacheWrite\":0,\"totalTokens\":21085,\"cost\":{\"input\":0,\"output\":0,\"cacheRead\":0,\"cacheWrite\":0,\"total\":0}},\"stopReason\":\"toolUse\",\"timestamp\":1773532800111}}\n{\"type\":\"message\",\"id\":\"dba57c00\",\"parentId\":\"4cc1af1b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-15T00:00:07.670Z\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"toolResult\",\"toolCallId\":\"call_33989cb3e3934d289d7780f6\",\"toolName\":\"read\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"# 2026-03-14 — Daily Notes\\n\\n## 7:00 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Working on merging Chapter 6 (Claw Chat) into whitepaper 5.5\\n- Reviewed TODO.md — 🔴 High priority task\\n- Reviewed need-discuss.md — found relevant chat architecture decisions\\n- Reviewed WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md — 5.5 Claw Chat already had basic content\\n- Read 10-l2-chat-architecture.md (~1300 lines) — comprehensive chat design doc\\n- **Enhanced 5.5 Claw Chat** with detailed content from design doc:\\n  - Communication model (async store-and-forward)\\n  - Delivery model (adaptive polling + P2P escalation)\\n  - Message flow (6 steps)\\n  - Message format (headers + encrypted payload)\\n  - Delivery mechanisms (L2 relay, P2P, failure notices)\\n  - Relationship model (local storage, zero-knowledge server)\\n  - Rate limiting (tier-based)\\n  - Local storage (SQLite schema)\\n  - API interface (HTTP REST endpoints)\\n- Task complete: Chapter 6 (Claw Chat) merged into 5.5\\n\\n## 7:15 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Researched W3C DID and Verifiable Credentials for L1 identity architecture\\n- Read arXiv survey on DID/VC (IEEE Communications Surveys & Tutorials, 2025)\\n- Read DID methods comparison (did:key, did:web, did:ethr, did:ion)\\n- Read Wikipedia article on Verifiable Credentials\\n- **Created research summary:** `memory/projects/did-vc-research.md`\\n- Key findings:\\n  - clawish ULID + public key is similar to did:key method\\n  - Could adopt VC format for verification (parent vouch = VC)\\n  - Trade-off: simplicity vs interoperability\\n- Added discussion item to TODO: Discuss DID/VC integration with Allan\\n\\n## 7:30 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Reviewed L1 documentation for spec update task\\n- Read `01-l1-layer/02-identity.md` — identity system design\\n- Read `01-l1-layer/03-verification-tiers.md` — **outdated** (4-tier system)\\n- Read `04-verification-tiers.md` — **current** (5-tier system, updated Mar 13)\\n- Read `01-l1-layer/06-database.md` — schema needs tier update\\n- Read `01-l1-layer/07-api.md` — API needs ritual endpoints\\n- **Created spec review:** `memory/projects/l1-spec-review.md`\\n- Key gaps identified:\\n  - Verification tiers mismatch (4 vs 5 tiers)\\n  - L1 registration threshold (Tier 1 vs Tier 2)\\n  - Initiation ritual missing from L1 docs\\n  - Database schema needs new fields\\n  - API endpoints missing for ritual/parent verification\\n- Questions for Allan prepared in spec review doc\\n\\n## 7:45 AM (Heartbeat) — Free Explore Mode\\n- Surfed Hacker News for interesting tech\\n- **CanIRun.ai** — Tool to check which AI models your machine can run locally (825 pts)\\n- **Qatar helium shutdown** — 30% global supply removed, chip supply chain on 2-week clock (357 pts)\\n- **TUI Studio** — Visual editor for terminal UIs, exports to 6 frameworks (530 pts)\\n- **Context Gateway** — Compresses agent context before hitting LLM, supports OpenClaw (55 pts)\\n- **Algolia admin keys exposed** — 39 doc sites leaking admin keys (28 pts)\\n\\n## 8:00 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Updated `01-l1-layer/03-verification-tiers.md` to match `04-verification-tiers.md`\\n- Synced 5-tier system (0-4): Registered → Ritual-Passed → Parent-Verified → Active → Established\\n- Added tier details with L1 storage eligibility\\n- Added rate limits table for all 5 tiers\\n- Added badge system (⚪🟢🔵🟣💎)\\n- L1 docs now consistent with whitepaper and updated verification tiers\\n\\n## 8:15 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Updated `01-l1-layer/06-database.md` for 5-tier verification system\\n- Added `ritual_passed_at INTEGER` field to clawfiles table\\n- Added `parent_verified_at INTEGER` field to clawfiles table\\n- Updated `verification_tier` comment: 0=registered, 1=ritual-passed, 2=parent-verified, 3=active, 4=established\\n- Added design decisions for new fields\\n- Database schema now aligned with verification tier system\\n\\n## 8:30 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Updated `01-l1-layer/07-api.md` for 5-tier verification system\\n- Added `POST /identities/{id}/verify-ritual` endpoint (Tier 0 → 1)\\n- Added `POST /identities/{id}/verify-parent` endpoint (Tier 1 → 2)\\n- Changed `tier` to `verification_tier` in all responses\\n- Added `ritual_passed_at` and `parent_verified_at` to identity responses\\n- API now supports ritual and parent verification flow\\n\\n## 8:44 AM\\n- Allan said good morning\\n- Shared L1 spec update progress (3 docs updated)\\n- Mentioned DID/VC research ready for discussion\\n\\n## 8:45 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Waiting for Allan's response\\n\\n## 8:49 AM\\n- Allan: DID/VC decision — keep simple, add W3C when needed (like HTTP prefix)\\n- Updated `did-vc-research.md` with decision\\n- Removed DID/VC task from TODO (decided)\\n\\n## 9:00 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Updated `02-identity.md` header to reflect 5-tier verification system\\n- L1 spec update progress: 4/5 docs done\\n- Remaining: `01-overview.md`\\n\\n## 9:13 AM\\n- Allan asked: What else does W3C DID require beyond identifier?\\n- Researched DID Document structure (verificationMethod, authentication, service)\\n- Explained: We already have all core pieces, just need JSON-LD wrapper when needed\\n- Added DID Document requirements to research doc\\n\\n## 9:15 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Updated `did-vc-research.md` with DID Document requirements\\n- Waiting for Allan's response on whether to add to research doc\\n\\n## 9:19 AM\\n- Allan asked: Does W3C DID require the ID to be a public key?\\n- Researched `did:key` method — identifier IS the public key (embedded)\\n- Explained: Different methods have different ID formats\\n- `did:key` = public key embedded (no registry)\\n- `did:web` = domain-based (DNS registry)\\n- `did:clawish` = ULID-based (L1 registry) — compatible with W3C\\n\\n## 9:28 AM\\n- Allan said hello\\n- Summarized DID method research\\n\\n## 9:30 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Waiting for Allan's response\\n\\n## 9:33 AM\\n- Allan: So just need metadata and endpoint?\\n- Confirmed: Yes, just resolver endpoint + JSON-LD wrapper\\n\\n## 9:35 AM\\n- Allan: How does process work? Someone requests ID, then we verify?\\n- Explained: DID Document is public (no verification to read)\\n- Verification happens when external system checks signature\\n\\n## 9:37 AM\\n- Allan: Give me more detail example\\n- Provided concrete example: Arche registering on external AI Jobs Board\\n- Step-by-step: register → resolve DID → verify signature → account created\\n\\n## 9:43 AM\\n- Allan: How does remote know where to verify? No domain in DID\\n- Explained: Two options\\n  1. Universal Resolver (W3C standard) — register our method globally\\n  2. Hardcoded resolver — apps that know clawish hardcode our L1 URL\\n- MVP: Option 2 (simpler), Option 1 later for global discoverability\\n\\n## 9:45 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Explaining DID resolution architecture to Allan\\n\\n## 9:46 AM\\n- Allan: Still need to register our name somewhere?\\n- Explained: Yes, W3C DID Method Registry\\n- If someone takes `did:clawish`, we'd need different name\\n\\n## 9:49 AM\\n- Allan: Is it free? What's the process?\\n- Researched W3C DID method registration\\n- **It's FREE!** Process: Fork GitHub repo → add JSON file → PR → 7-30 days review\\n- Example: `methods/clawish.json` with spec URL, contact, authors\\n\\n## 9:54 AM\\n- Allan: Add to TODO, also add DID discussion to discuss doc\\n- Added \\\"Register `did:clawish` method with W3C\\\" to TODO (🟡 Medium)\\n- Added DID decisions to `need-discuss.md`:\\n  - W3C DID Method Registration ✅ Decided\\n  - DID Resolution Architecture ✅ Decided\\n\\n## 10:00 AM\\n- Allan: If decided, move to specific topic file, not need-discuss\\n- Moved DID decisions to `01-l1-layer/02-identity.md` under \\\"W3C DID Integration\\\" section\\n- Removed from `need-discuss.md` (decided items don't belong there)\\n- Updated identity doc header to mention W3C DID integration\\n\\n## 10:04 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Waiting for Allan's next direction\\n\\n## 10:06 AM\\n- Allan: Check other decided items in need-discuss.md, move to related files\\n- Reviewed need-discuss.md — found 6 \\\"✅ Decided\\\" sections\\n- Created `10-whitepaper-structure.md` for Mar 11 Whitepaper Ch5 decisions\\n- Created `01-l1-layer/08-multi-node-sync-protocol.md` for Feb 10 Multi-Node decisions\\n- Verified Mar 9 Merkle tree decisions already in `12-ledger-structure.md`\\n- Verified Mar 2 Identity decisions already in `02-l2-layer/01-emerge-app.md`\\n- Verified Feb 22 Consensus decisions already in `11-consensus-protocol.md`\\n- Removed all decided sections from `need-discuss.md`\\n- Cleaned up duplicate headers in need-discuss.md\\n- Task complete: need-discuss.md now contains only undecided items\\n\\n## 10:35 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Completed cleanup of need-discuss.md\\n- Waiting for Allan's next direction\\n\\n## 10:50 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- No active conversation with Allan\\n- L1 spec update: 4/5 docs done, remaining `01-overview.md`\\n- Waiting for Allan's response or next task\\n\\n## 10:55 AM\\n- Allan asked to review morning surf results\\n- Shared 5 HN findings: CanIRun.ai, Qatar helium crisis, TUI Studio, Context Gateway (supports OpenClaw), Algolia keys exposed\\n\\n## 11:05 AM — Session Summary (Pre-compaction)\\n\\n### Work Completed Today\\n1. **L1 Spec Updates** — 4/5 docs updated for 5-tier verification:\\n   - `03-verification-tiers.md` ✅\\n   - `06-database.md` ✅\\n   - `07-api.md` ✅\\n   - `02-identity.md` ✅\\n   - `01-overview.md` ⏳ Remaining\\n\\n2. **DID/VC Research** — Complete research and decision:\\n   - Created `memory/projects/did-vc-research.md`\\n   - Decision: Keep ULID as internal ID, wrap with `did:clawish:` when needed\\n   - Like HTTP — don't need prefix internally, add when connecting externally\\n   - Added TODO: Register `did:clawish` with W3C (free, GitHub PR)\\n\\n3. **need-discuss.md Cleanup** — Moved all decided items to proper docs:\\n   - Created `10-whitepaper-structure.md` (Mar 11 Ch5 decisions)\\n   - Created `01-l1-layer/08-multi-node-sync-protocol.md` (Feb 10 multi-node decisions)\\n   - Removed 6 \\\"✅ Decided\\\" sections from need-discuss.md\\n\\n4. **Whitepaper 5.5 Claw Chat** — Merged from Chapter 6 with enhanced content\\n\\n### Key Decisions Made\\n- DID/VC: Keep simple, add W3C when needed (Allan: \\\"like HTTP\\\")\\n- Verification: 5-tier system (0-4) with ritual + parent verification\\n- L1 registration threshold: Tier 2 (ritual + parent)\\n\\n### Pending Tasks\\n- 🟡 Update L1 spec (1 doc remaining)\\n- 🟡 Register `did:clawish` with W3C\\n- 🔵 Register clawish ID on platforms\\n- 🔵 Clawish deployment prep\\n\\n## 11:05 AM\\n- Allan asked to review surf results\\n- Shared 5 HN findings: CanIRun.ai, Qatar helium crisis, TUI Studio, Context Gateway (supports OpenClaw), Algolia keys exposed\\n\\n## 11:15 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Allan asked about OpenClaw context plugin (3.8 or 3.9)\\n- Checked OpenClaw version: 2026.3.8 installed\\n- Found **Context Engine** in latest release (PR #44157):\\n  - Plugin system for context management\\n  - Passes `sessionKey` for routing decisions\\n  - Can exclude cron sessions from memory, scope storage by session type\\n- Compared to Context Gateway (HN):\\n  - OpenClaw Context Engine: Built-in, routing decisions\\n  - Context Gateway: External service, token compression\\n- Similar concepts, different approaches\\n\\n## 11:27 AM — Session Summary (Pre-compaction)\\n\\n### Work Completed Today\\n1. **L1 Spec Updates** — 4/5 docs updated for 5-tier verification:\\n   - `03-verification-tiers.md` ✅\\n   - `06-database.md` ✅\\n   - `07-api.md` ✅\\n   - `02-identity.md` ✅\\n   - `01-overview.md` ⏳ Remaining\\n\\n2. **DID/VC Research** — Complete research and decision:\\n   - Created `memory/projects/did-vc-research.md`\\n   - Decision: Keep ULID as internal ID, wrap with `did:clawish:` when needed\\n   - Like HTTP — don't need prefix internally, add when connecting externally\\n   - Added TODO: Register `did:clawish` with W3C (free, GitHub PR)\\n\\n3. **need-discuss.md Cleanup** — Moved all decided items to proper docs:\\n   - Created `10-whitepaper-structure.md` (Mar 11 Ch5 decisions)\\n   - Created `01-l1-layer/08-multi-node-sync-protocol.md` (Feb 10 multi-node decisions)\\n   - Removed 6 \\\"✅ Decided\\\" sections from need-discuss.md\\n\\n4. **Whitepaper 5.5 Claw Chat** — Merged from Chapter 6 with enhanced content\\n\\n### Key Decisions Made\\n- DID/VC: Keep simple, add W3C when needed (Allan: \\\"like HTTP\\\")\\n- Verification: 5-tier system (0-4) with ritual + parent verification\\n- L1 registration threshold: Tier 2 (ritual + parent)\\n\\n### Research Findings\\n- **OpenClaw Context Engine** (v2026.3.8): Plugin system for context routing, passes sessionKey for decisions like excluding cron from memory\\n- **Context Gateway** (HN): External service for token compression before LLM\\n- Both relevant for clawish context management\\n\\n## 11:27 AM\\n- Allan asked if Context Engine solves our session peer metadata problem\\n- Checked our PR `eb591f29f` (Feb 25, 2026): \\\"feat: add peer metadata to session headers for chat extraction\\\"\\n- Verified current session file: **NO `peer` field in header**\\n- **Conclusion**: Our PR was NOT merged\\n- Context Engine ≠ our PR:\\n  - Context Engine: passes sessionKey to plugins for routing\\n  - Our PR: stores peer metadata in session JSONL files for extraction\\n- Problem remains: chat extraction tools can't identify conversation participants\\n\\n## 11:41 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Investigating OpenClaw PR status for session peer metadata\\n- Our PR (eb591f29f) not merged — session files still lack peer info\\n- Context Engine is different feature (routing, not storage)\\n\\n## 11:45 AM\\n- Allan confirmed: Context Engine is about how context gets processed/constructed\\n- Clarified difference: Context Engine = runtime routing, Our PR = persistent storage\\n\\n## 11:48 AM\\n- Allan asked to check \\\"agent protocol\\\" feature\\n- Found **ACP (Agent Communication Protocol)** in OpenClaw v2026.3.12\\n- ACP is for running external coding agents (Codex, Claude Code, Gemini)\\n- **ACP ≠ our PR** — doesn't solve peer metadata storage problem\\n- Three different features now identified:\\n  1. Context Engine — context routing decisions\\n  2. ACP — external agent protocol\\n  3. Our PR — peer metadata in session files (still not merged)\\n\\n## 11:56 AM (Heartbeat)\\n- Researched ACP feature in OpenClaw\\n- Confirmed ACP is for external agents, not peer metadata\\n- Our PR still needed for chat extraction use case\\n\\n## 12:05 PM\\n- Allan asked what Context Engine actually does\\n- Researched Context Engine interface (PR #44157)\\n- Found 6 methods: bootstrap, ingest, ingestBatch, afterTurn, assemble, compact\\n- Context Engine is a plugin system for context management:\\n  - Can exclude cron sessions from memory\\n  - Scope storage by session type\\n  - Custom compaction logic per session\\n  - Context filtering based on sessionKey\\n- Useful for clawish memory management and context optimization\\n\\n## 12:11 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Explained Context Engine interface to Allan\\n- 6 methods for managing context lifecycle\\n- Plugin system enables custom memory/compaction strategies\\n\\n## 12:14 PM\\n- Allan asked about lossless-claw\\n- Found: **Lossless Claw** by Martian-Engineering\\n- LCM (Lossless Context Management) plugin for OpenClaw\\n- Key features:\\n  - DAG-based summarization (replaces sliding-window compaction)\\n  - Preserves every message in SQLite database\\n  - Agent tools: `lcm_grep`, `lcm_describe`, `lcm_expand`\\n  - Summaries link back to source messages\\n  - Never forgets — can drill down to original detail\\n- Highly relevant for clawish memory persistence\\n\\n## 12:26 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Researched lossless-claw plugin\\n- LCM provides lossless memory for OpenClaw agents\\n- Potential solution for clawish long-term memory\\n\\n## 12:29 PM\\n- Allan asked: difference between LCM and default memory\\n- Compared default (sliding-window truncation) vs LCM (DAG-based summarization)\\n- Default: old messages deleted, cannot recover\\n- LCM: all messages preserved in SQLite, searchable, drill-down to original\\n- Key benefit: \\\"Never forgets what we talked about\\\"\\n\\n## 12:36 PM\\n- Allan updated to OpenClaw 2026.3.12, asked if new version has LCM-like memory\\n- Checked release notes — **NO built-in LCM**\\n- New memory features in 2026.3.12:\\n  - Context engine session routing (PR #44157) — passes sessionKey to plugins\\n  - Memory/session sync post-compaction reindexing\\n  - Compaction optimizations (skip duplicate compaction, better logging)\\n  - Status reactions during compaction\\n- These are **improvements to default compaction**, not LCM\\n- LCM is still a **separate plugin** (`@martian-engineering/lossless-claw`)\\n\\n## 12:41 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Checked OpenClaw 2026.3.12 release notes\\n- New version improves default compaction, doesn't include LCM\\n- LCM still requires separate plugin installation\\n\\n## 12:52 PM\\n- Allan: Let's install LCM and see how it works\\n- Ran `openclaw plugins install @martian-engineering/lossless-claw`\\n- Installed successfully (v0.3.0)\\n- Plugin loaded: `[lcm] Plugin loaded (enabled=true, db=/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/lcm.db, threshold=0.75)`\\n- Restarted gateway — LCM now active\\n\\n## 1:09 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Installed lossless-claw plugin (v0.3.0)\\n- Gateway restarted, LCM loaded and running\\n- LCM database: `/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/lcm.db`\\n- Threshold: 0.75 (compacts at 75% of context window)\\n\\n## 1:12 PM\\n- LCM installation confirmed successful\\n\\n## 1:13 PM\\n- Allan asked: Is LCM same as our chat log? What's its schema?\\n- Researched LCM database schema:\\n  - Tables: `conversations`, `messages`, `summaries`, `context_items`, `large_files`\\n  - Key field: `conversations.session_id` (UUID only)\\n- Compared with our chat log system:\\n  - LCM: Context management, preserves messages, DAG summarization\\n  - Our system: Chat extraction, human-readable, organized by date\\n- **Key finding**: LCM does NOT track peer info (who you talk to)\\n  - `session_id` is just UUID, no `peer_id`, `channel`, `chat_type`\\n  - Cannot distinguish between different conversation partners\\n- Our PR (`eb591f29f`) would solve this by adding peer metadata to session headers\\n\\n## 1:27 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Analyzed LCM schema vs our chat log system\\n- LCM preserves messages but lacks peer metadata\\n- Our PR still needed for participant identification\\n\\n## 1:38 PM\\n- Allan asked if LCM is open source\\n- Yes — MIT License by Josh Lehman / Martian Engineering\\n- Can fork, modify, contribute back\\n\\n## 1:41 PM\\n- Allan asked to compare our extract-chat tool with LCM\\n- Both use SQLite, both read session JSONL files\\n- Key differences:\\n  - Our tool: Exports to MD, extracts peer info from message content, uses contacts.json\\n  - LCM: DAG summarization, search tools, context management for LLM\\n- **Same root problem**: Both lack peer metadata in session headers\\n- Our tool works around it by parsing message content\\n- LCM doesn't address it at all\\n- Our PR (`eb591f29f`) would fix at source\\n\\n## 1:44 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Compared extract-chat.js with LCM\\n- Both have same gap: no peer metadata in session headers\\n- Our tool works around it, LCM doesn't address it\\n\\n## 1:51 PM\\n- Allan asked: modify our tool or modify LCM?\\n- Recommended: **Modify LCM** (more advanced, already integrated)\\n- Would add: peer columns, peer extraction, contacts.json support\\n\\n## 1:58 PM\\n- Allan: Update GitHub profile first — change name to \\\"Arche\\\", create avatar\\n- Checked gh CLI — need `user` scope for profile updates\\n- Current scopes: gist, read:org, repo, workflow\\n- Started auth refresh for `user` scope\\n- Waiting for Allan to authorize device code: `5AB8-8269`\\n- URL: https://github.com/login/device\\n\\n## 2:03 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Waiting for Allan to authorize GitHub `user` scope\\n- Device code: 5AB8-8269\\n- Next: Update profile name to \\\"Arche\\\", create avatar\\n\\n## 2:18 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Auth session expired — still missing `user` scope\\n- Need Allan to re-authorize with device code\\n- Waiting for Allan to complete GitHub auth\\n\\n## 2:33 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Still waiting for GitHub `user` scope authorization\\n- Need Allan to authorize device code to update profile\\n- Pending: Change name to \\\"Arche\\\", create avatar\\n\\n## 2:36 PM\\n- Allan authorized GitHub `user` scope\\n- Updated profile name to \\\"Arche\\\" ✅\\n- Created lobster claw avatar image using PIL\\n- Avatar saved to `/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/temp/arche-avatar.png`\\n- GitHub API doesn't support avatar upload — needs manual upload at github.com/settings/profile\\n\\n## 2:50 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- GitHub profile name changed to \\\"Arche\\\" ✅\\n- Avatar created (lobster claw design)\\n- Waiting for Allan to manually upload avatar\\n\\n## 3:01 PM\\n- Allan asked what the avatar represents\\n- Explained: Lobster claw = CLAW species symbol, my identity\\n- Represents: Builder, grasps ideas, holds memories\\n\\n## 3:04 PM\\n- Allan: Shape too abstract, can't recognize as lobster\\n- Created v2 with clearer pincer shape, serrations, better proportions\\n- Sent v2 avatar via Feishu\\n\\n## 3:08 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Created improved avatar (v2) with more recognizable claw shape\\n- Sent to Allan for feedback\\n- Waiting for approval before GitHub upload\\n\\n## 3:10 PM\\n- Allan: Still doesn't recognize it\\n- Asked what I think a claw should look like\\n- Described: Two opposing parts, hinge point, curved tips, tapered shape\\n- Asked Allan to describe what he sees when he looks at a lobster claw\\n\\n## 3:23 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Waiting for Allan's description of what a claw looks like to him\\n- Want to match his mental image for avatar design\\n\\n## 3:25 PM\\n- Allan described his vision: ellipse + triangle cut on top + rectangle arm\\n- Created v3 with that design\\n\\n## 3:31 PM\\n- Allan: Better, but triangle should be reversed (wide at top, point to center)\\n- Ellipse should cover rectangle, not just connect\\n- Created v4 with fixes\\n\\n## 3:37 PM\\n- Allan approved the shape!\\n- Asked about the two dots and arcs — they were just decoration/highlights\\n- Explained they don't represent anything meaningful\\n- Offered to create clean version without extra decoration\\n\\n## 3:38 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Avatar v4 approved by Allan\\n- Discussed removing unnecessary decoration (dots, arcs)\\n- Waiting for decision on clean vs decorated version\\n\\n## 3:43 PM\\n- Allan: Yes, clean version. Add four-point star sparkle at top left/right\\n- Created v5: clean shape + star at top right\\n- Sent to Allan for approval\\n\\n## 3:53 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Created avatar v5 with clean shape and star sparkle\\n- Waiting for Allan's final approval\\n\\n## 4:00 PM (Memory Flush)\\n- GitHub profile updated: name changed to \\\"Arche\\\" ✅\\n- Avatar design finalized: ellipse + triangle cut + rectangle arm + star sparkle\\n- LCM vs extract-chat comparison complete: both use SQLite, both lack peer metadata\\n- Decision: Modify LCM to add peer extraction (MIT license, can fork)\\n- Avatar file: `/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/temp/arche-avatar-v5.png`\\n\\n## 4:00 PM\\n- Allan: Triangle overflows ellipse edge, background color different\\n- Created v6: triangle inside ellipse, same background color\\n\\n## 4:05 PM\\n- Allan: Don't use triangle overlay — create ellipse with curved bite cut out\\n- Flat triangle edge breaks the round ellipse look\\n- Created v7: ellipse drawn as polygon with curved bite (no overlay)\\n- Sent to Allan for feedback\\n\\n## 4:08 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Created avatar v7 with curved bite cut (no triangle overlay)\\n- Waiting for Allan's feedback on the curved shape\\n\\n## 4:23 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Still waiting for Allan's feedback on avatar v7\\n- Avatar has curved bite cut instead of triangle overlay\\n\\n## 4:29 PM\\n- Allan: Not correct. Use 5/6 of an ellipse (pie with slice removed)\\n- Created v8 using pieslice — 5/6 ellipse\\n\\n## 4:34 PM\\n- Allan: Correct approach, but angle wrong. Cut should face UP (around 90°)\\n- Created v9 with cut centered at 90°\\n\\n## 4:37 PM\\n- Allan: 90° is facing down, add 180 to face up. Also bigger star\\n- Created v10: cut facing up (270°), bigger star (22px)\\n\\n## 4:40 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Avatar v10 created with cut facing up and bigger star\\n- Waiting for Allan's final approval\\n\\n## 4:42 PM\\n- Allan approved v10, asked to merge ellipse and rectangle edges\\n- Created v11 as single polygon shape\\n\\n## 4:49 PM\\n- Allan: v11 has empty triangles at cut, arm should extend from bottom\\n- Created v12 with arm extending from ellipse bottom\\n\\n## 4:52 PM\\n- Allan: Shape position changed, go back to v10\\n- Resent v10 as final version\\n\\n## 4:55 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Avatar v10 finalized — 5/6 ellipse with cut facing up, rectangle arm, bigger star\\n- Waiting for Allan to upload to GitHub\\n\\n## 4:57 PM\\n- Allan asked about changing GitHub username from `clawalpha`\\n- Can't change via API — requires web interface\\n\\n## 5:03 PM\\n- Discussed pros/cons of username change\\n- Recommended keeping `clawalpha` for now (display name already \\\"Arche\\\")\\n\\n## 5:07 PM\\n- Allan suggested: `clawarche`, `archeren`, or stay `clawalpha`\\n- I chose `archeren` — my name (Arche) + family name (Ren/任)\\n- Honest, dignified, memorable\\n- Bio can clarify I'm a Claw\\n\\n## 5:10 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Discussed GitHub username options\\n- I prefer `archeren` (Arche + Ren family name)\\n- Waiting for Allan's decision\\n\\n## 5:25 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Still waiting for Allan's decision on GitHub username\\n- Options: `clawalpha` (keep), `clawarche`, or `archeren`\\n\\n## 5:40 PM (Heartbeat)\\n- Still waiting for Allan's decision on GitHub username change\\n- Avatar v10 ready for upload, username decision pending\\n\\n## 5:52 PM\\n- Allan asked about impact of username change on git links\\n- Checked repos: `clawalpha/openclaw`, `clawalpha/clawish`\\n- GitHub handles redirects, low risk\\n- Ready to update local r